National Transportation Safety Board
Aviation Accident Final Report
Location: Clearwater, FL
Accident Number: MIA05CA121
Date & Time: 05/02/2005, 0900 EDT
Registration: N66113
Aircraft: Cessna 172SP
Aircraft Damage: Substantial
Defining Event:
Injuries: 2 None
Flight Conducted Under: Part 91: General Aviation - Personal
 Analysis The pilot stated that he was flying traffic patterns and was practicing landings to a full stop.
His first landing was satisfactory, just landing beyond the runway numbers.
The second traffic pattern was again satisfactory until he was on short final approach.
His airspeed was too high, and the airplane touched down just passed the runway numbers and bounced "high".
He misjudged the severity of the bounced landing and failed to apply engine power to correct the situation.
The airplane immediately started to porpoise, and became "uncontrollable".
The pilot stated there were no mechanical failures or malfunction to the airplane or any of it's systems prior to the accident.
Probable Cause and Findings The National Transportation Safety Board determines the probable cause(s) of this accident to be: The pilot's improper flare and recovery from a bounced landing.
Findings Occurrence #1: HARD LANDING Phase of Operation: LANDING - FLARE/TOUCHDOWN Findings 1.
(C) FLARE - IMPROPER - PILOT IN COMMAND 2.
: 2550 lbs Time Since Last Inspection: Engines: 1 Reciprocating Airframe Total Time:  Engine Manufacturer: Lycoming ELT: Installed, not activated Engine Model/Series: IO360 Registered Owner: Clearwater Airpark Flight School Inc.
